Hello I watched the video so I would have knowledge about panic attacks. I don't experience them, but I'd like to know how to help people who do. What should I do when a person around me experiences it? Can you guys give me tips about things you do when you experience it? Thank you so much!

panic attack feel like you have NO IDENTITY, that you stop knowing who you are because everything you learnt is an illusion and subject to doubt and destruction, you become overwhelmed within the realm of the unknown and you lose track of what is what, like in the middle of an ocean with an infinite depth with no solid reference below. I've experienced it a lot, i write about it accurately. mine were induced by marijuana and a recent PTSD. writing about it made me a different man, i understand myself more every day and it helped me process my past and come out as a more definitive being, it is a spiritual experience that made me closer to the universe and the concept of God. I wish all of those with panic attacks the best and remember, do not just dismiss it, it is an opportunity for you to understand, a gift, so take it and process it.

I had anxiety during 2020, but I was lucky enough to have such incredible, supportive, amazing friends and family who let me talk to them and comforted me through it all. Now it's almost 2022, and my anxiety is gone! Of course, I might get a little more nervous about something than other people will, but I'm still young, so there was enough time to do something about it. I had a total of only two panic attacks during that time, and both times I was extremely scared of dying. I thought I was going to die and those thoughts wouldn't leave my mind. So I started to take care of myself. Every time I looked in the mirror I'd think nice things about myself and what I saw in the reflection. I remember when the attacks happened, I'd always think "This too, shall pass" and start to feel a little better. I think both times my attacks happened it was because of a lack of sleep. The first time it happened I had no idea what was going on so I locked myself in the bathroom and texted my friend about what was happening, and he comforted me through it. The second time it was a smaller attack and wasn't as scary because I knew what to do and knew what was going on this time, but either way it's still a fright. My attacks didn't last the whole day, only for a few minutes or a little longer, but I would still be a bit shaken up for the rest of the day. You all are so strong, and I believe in you. I made it, so I have no doubt that you all will too. I'm forever grateful to everyone who helped me with my anxiety, so I want to help people with theirs in return. I'm the mom/therapist friend, so if any of you ever want to talk, I'm hereüíúStay strong!
For me face the fear ! Head on and be relentless and boom I was cured üëä

My panic attacks got so bad when I was 18, I wasn't able to leave my house for days because I was scared I might get one in public and have no one around.. I lost 14 pounds within 3- 4weeks... I'd cry almost every night because I felt weak and tired of it all but as many people struggling with mental health, I was scared of going to therapy and getting help. One night at 1am I told my parents that I'm ready to see a professional and that is the best decision I have ever made to this day. It only took one session with someone who understood me. My appetite started improving and slowly but surely I was starting to stress less about my panic attacks. I haven't had one since, so it's been 4 years now. To anyone who's going through this: tell yourself you're ok and mean it! You are going to be fine. It will pass trust me! This is how I got out of a very dark place in my life and it took me months but once you start thinking optimistically and clearing your head of such bad thoughts, the attacks will leave once and for all!
Thank you Ted-Ed video like these makes me realize I am not alone in fighting my panic attacks.
